<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5905&amp;p=54758#p54758"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Do you think it's worth messing with 3D modeling in order to make better 2D graphics (such as in Donkey Kong Country) ?<br /></div><br />The success of Myst and Final Fantasy VII (for backgrounds) and DKC series, Toy Story, Uniracers, Super Mario RPG, and Mario vs. Donkey Kong (for sprites) says yes.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />I could model simple geometric shapes with Blender, but honnestly I couldn't see how you could possibly model an human - even less how you could animate it.<br /></div><br />A human starts as 19 ellipsoids: head, upper torso, lower torso, and 4 limbs. Each limb is the upper limb, lower limb, palm/sole, and a set of fingers/toes. Animate that framework and render it, and it'll look roughly like the characters from the fighting game Ballz 3D. A bit more tweaking of each ellipsoid, and you have something over which to draw a sprite sheet.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Tue Jan 05, 2010 1:30 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
