<title type="html"><![CDATA[Game- ready model shops]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5905&amp;p=54755#p54755"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Not nesdev related, but interesting (we're in the general forum).<br />Do you think it's worth messing with 3D modeling in order to make better 2D graphics (such as in Donkey Kong Country) ?<br /><br />I could model simple geometric shapes with Blender, but honnestly I couldn't see how you could possibly model an human - even less how you could animate it.<br /></div><br /><br />3d models could be useful for <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotoscoping" class="postlink">rotoscoping</a> animations for some kinds of objects.  For a 3d human model, recordings from motion capture sensors seem like the way to go.<br /><br />So any 3d models are useless on NES alone, but I think anyone who's not a talented artist already, could always use some help with references for perspective and scale.  I've considered an approach like that for a later project.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=10">Memblers</a> — Tue Jan 05, 2010 1:20 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
